    "%run ../initscript.py\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "from scipy import stats\n",
    "from scipy.stats import multivariate_normal\n",
    "from ipywidgets import *\n",
    "from IPython.display import display, HTML\n",
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures\n",
    "from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n",
    "import warnings\n",
    "warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')\n",
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "\n",
    "import sys\n",
    "sys.path.append('modules')\n",
    "\n",
    "from DesignMat import Polynomial, Gaussian, Sigmoidal\n",
    "from Regressor import LeastSquares, Bayesian, Empirical\n",
    "\n",
    "def sinusoidal(x):\n",
    "    return np.sin(2 * np.pi * x)\n",
    "\n",
    "def create_data(func, sample_size, std, domain=[0, 1]):\n",
    "    x = np.linspace(*domain, sample_size)\n",
    "    np.random.shuffle(x)\n",
    "    t = func(x) + np.random.normal(scale=std, size=x.shape)\n",
    "    return x, t\n",
    "\n",
    "toggle()"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Linear Models for Regression"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Basis Functions\n",
    "Example of basis functions: polynomial function $\\phi_j({x}) = {x}^j$, and other nonlinear basis functions, such as Gaussian and Sigmoidal:\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\\phi_j (x) = \\exp \\left\\{ - \\frac{(x-\\mu_j)^2}{2s^2} \\right\\} \\text{ or } \\phi_j (x) = \\sigma \\left( \\frac{x-\\mu_j}{s} \\right) \\text{ where } \\sigma(z) = \\frac{1}{1+\\exp(-z)} \\nonumber\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "The code replicates Figure 3.1 in PRML."
   ]
  },

    "x_train, t_train = create_data(sinusoidal, 10, 0.25)\n",
    "\n",
    "x_test = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)\n",
    "t_test = sinusoidal(x_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "basis_funcs = {'Polynomial': [8], 'Gaussian': [np.linspace(0, 1, 8), 0.1], 'Sigmoidal': [np.linspace(0, 1, 8), 10]}\n",
    "\n",
    "fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\n",
    "\n",
    "for i, (key, value) in enumerate(basis_funcs.items()):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    phi_train = globals()[key](*value).dm(x_train)\n",
    "    phi_test  = globals()[key](*value).dm(x_test)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    t, t_std = LeastSquares().fit(phi_train, t_train).predict_dist(phi_test)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.subplot(2, 2, i+1)\n",
    "    plt.scatter(x_train, t_train, facecolor=\"none\", edgecolor=\"b\", s=50, label=\"training data\")\n",
    "    plt.plot(x_test, t_test, label=\"$\\sin(2\\pi x)$\")\n",
    "    plt.plot(x_test, t, label=\"prediction\")\n",
    "    plt.fill_between(x_test, t - t_std, t + t_std, color=\"orange\", alpha=0.5, label=\"std.\")\n",
    "    plt.annotate(\"{}\".format(key), xy=(0.05, -.8))\n",
    "    plt.legend()\n",
    "    \n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "toggle()"
   ]

   "source": [
    "x_train, t_train = create_data(sinusoidal, 10, 0.25)\n",
    "\n",
    "x_test = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)\n",
    "t_test = sinusoidal(x_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "# set degree = 9 because it's the most complicated polynomial model for 10 data points\n",
    "phi_train = Polynomial(9).dm(x_train)\n",
    "phi_test  = Polynomial(9).dm(x_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 4))\n",
    "for i, alpha in enumerate([0, 1e-3, 1]):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # alpha is the regularization coefficient\n",
    "    t = LeastSquares(alpha).fit(phi_train, t_train).predict(phi_test)\n",
    "   \n",
    "    plt.subplot(1, 3, i+1)\n",
    "    plt.scatter(x_train, t_train, facecolor=\"none\", edgecolor=\"b\", s=50, label=\"training data\")\n",
    "    plt.plot(x_test, t_test, c=\"g\", label=\"$\\sin(2\\pi x)$\")\n",
    "    plt.plot(x_test, t, c=\"r\", label=\"fitting\")\n",
    "    plt.ylim(-1.5, 1.5)\n",
    "    plt.legend(loc=1)\n",
    "    plt.annotate(r\"n={}, $\\lambda$={}\".format(9, alpha), xy=(0.05, -1.2))\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "toggle()"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Stochastic Gradient Descent"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "- When the training data set is very large or received in a stream, a direct solution using the normal equations of the least squares may not be possible.\n",
    "\t\t\n",
    "- An alternative approach is the \\textit{stochastic gradient descent} algorithm.\n",
    "\t\t\n",
    "- The total error function\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "E_{\\mathcal{D}}(\\mathbf{w}) & = \\frac{1}{2}  \\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \\mathbf{w}^\\intercal \\phi(x_{i}))^2 \\equiv \\sum_{i=1}^{n} E_{i}(\\mathbf{w}) \\nonumber\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "- In general, the stochastic gradient descent algorithm is applying\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\\mathbf{w}^{\\tau + 1} = \\mathbf{w}^\\tau - \\eta \\bigtriangledown_{\\mathbf{w}} E_i \\nonumber\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "    where ${\\tau}$ is the iteration number and $\\eta$ is a learning rate parameter.\n",
    "\t\t\n",
    "- When the error function is the sum-of-squares function (the order of evaluation does not change the result), then the algorithm is\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\\mathbf{w}^{\\tau + 1} = \\mathbf{w}^\\tau + \\eta \\left(y_i - \\mathbf{w}^{(\\tau) \\intercal}\\phi_i\\right)\\phi_i \\nonumber\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "Data is generated by a trigonomietric function\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "t = w_0 + w_1 \\sin(x) + w_2 \\cos(x) \\nonumber\n",
    "\\end{align}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"

     "execution_count": 5,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }

   "source": [
    "def trigonometric(x, w=[1.85, 0.57, 4.37]): \n",
    "    return np.dot(w, [np.ones_like(x), np.sin(x), np.cos(x)])\n",
    "\n",
    "x_trig_train, t_trig_train = create_data(trigonometric, 20, 1, [0, 4.0*np.pi])\n",
    "\n",
    "x_trig_test = np.linspace(0, 4.0*np.pi, 100)\n",
    "t_trig_test = trigonometric(x_trig_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "# design matrix\n",
    "phi = np.array([np.ones_like(x_trig_train), np.sin(x_trig_train), np.cos(x_trig_train)]).transpose()\n",
    "\n",
    "# we set initial w = 0\n",
    "w = np.zeros(phi.shape[1])\n",
    "\n",
    "eta = 0.25\n",
    "# since we have 20 samples, we use gradient from each sample in order\n",
    "for i in range(20):\n",
    "    w = w + eta * (t_trig_train[i] - np.dot(w.T, phi[i])) * phi[i]\n",
    "\n",
    "t_predicted = trigonometric(x_trig_test, w)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.scatter(x_trig_train, t_trig_train, facecolor=\"none\", edgecolor=\"b\", s=50, label=\"training data\")\n",
    "plt.plot(x_trig_test, t_trig_test, c=\"g\", label=\"trigonometric\")\n",
    "plt.plot(x_trig_test,t_predicted, c='r', label=\"fitting\")\n",
    "plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 0.27), loc=2, borderaxespad=0.5)\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "toggle()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Bias-Variance Decomposition\n",
    "\n",
    "Illustrate bias and variance with a regularization parameter $\\ln \\lambda \\in \\{2.6, -0.31, -2.4\\}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "- In `x_train, t_train`, we generate 100 datasets, and each has 25 sinusoidal data points\n",
    "\n",
    "- Graphs in the first row demonstrate variance\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "\\mathbb{E}_{\\mathcal D}\\left[ \\left( f(\\mathbf{x}; \\mathcal D) - \\mathbb{E}_{\\mathcal D}\\left[ f(\\mathbf{x}; \\mathcal D)\\right] \\right)^2  \\right]\n",
    "\\end{align*}\n",
    "   \n",
    "   where each curve is represented by a function $f(\\mathbf{x}; \\mathcal D)$ with given dataset $\\mathcal D$. When $\\mathcal D$ is given, $f(\\mathbf{x}; \\mathcal D)$ is a fitting function based on the dataset (for clarity, only 20 of the 100 fits are shown). Their average $\\mathbb{E}_{\\mathcal D}\\left[ f(\\mathbf{x}; \\mathcal D)\\right]$ gives the fitting curve of graphs in the second row.\n",
    "   \n",
    "- Thus, graphs in the second row demonstrate bias$^2$\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "\\left( \\mathbb{E}_{\\mathcal D}\\left[f(\\mathbf{x}; \\mathcal D)\\right] - h(\\mathbf{x}) \\right)^2   \n",
    "\\end{align*}\n",
    "    \n",
    "where $h(\\mathbf{x})$ the optimal prediction, i.e., $\\sin (2 \\pi x)$ in our case.\n",
    "    \n",
    "The last graph shows variance and bias$^2$ by varying $\\lambda$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/html": [
       "\n",
       "        <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"code_toggle(this); return false;\">show code</a>\n",
       "    "
      ],
      "text/plain": [
       "<IPython.core.display.HTML object>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 14,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "funcs = {'Polynomial': [24], 'Gaussian': [np.linspace(0, 1, 24), 0.1], 'Sigmoidal': [np.linspace(0, 1, 24), 10]}\n",
    "\n",
    "x_test = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)\n",
    "t_test = sinusoidal(x_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "def bias_and_var(fname):\n",
    "    phi_test = globals()[fname](*funcs[fname]).dm(x_test)\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for loc, alpha in enumerate([2.6, -0.31, -2.4]):\n",
    "        plt.subplot(2, 3, loc+1)\n",
    "        # We have 100 data sets, each having 25 data points\n",
    "        x_train, t_train = zip(*[create_data(sinusoidal, 25, 0.8) for i in range(100)])\n",
    "        phi_train = [globals()[fname](*funcs[fname]).dm(x) for x in x_train]\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # t[i] is an array contains the prediction values for x_test and \n",
    "        # the fitting function is derived based on i-th data set\n",
    "        t = [LeastSquares(np.exp(alpha)).fit(phi, t).predict(phi_test) for phi, t in zip(phi_train, t_train)]\n",
    "        # For clarity, only 20 of the 100 fits are shown\n",
    "        for i in range(20):\n",
    "            plt.plot(x_test, t[i], c=\"orange\")\n",
    "            \n",
    "        plt.annotate(r\"$\\ln \\lambda={}$\".format(alpha), xy=(0.05, -1.2))        \n",
    "        plt.ylim(-1.5, 1.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "        plt.subplot(2, 3, loc+4)\n",
    "        plt.plot(x_test, t_test, c=\"g\", label=\"$\\sin(2\\pi x)$\")\n",
    "        plt.plot(x_test, np.asarray(t).mean(axis=0), c=\"r\", label=\"fitting\")\n",
    "        plt.ylim(-1.5, 1.5)\n",
    "        plt.legend()\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 5))\n",
    "    x_train, t_train = zip(*[create_data(sinusoidal, 25, 0.8) for i in range(100)])\n",
    "    phi_train = [globals()[fname](*funcs[fname]).dm(x) for x in x_train]\n",
    "    alpha_range = np.linspace(-2.6, 1.5, 30)\n",
    "    t = [[LeastSquares(np.exp(alpha)).fit(phi, t).predict(phi_test) for phi, t in zip(phi_train, t_train)]\n",
    "         for alpha in alpha_range]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    bias2 = ((np.asarray(t).mean(axis=1) - t_test) ** 2).mean(axis=1) #(3.46)\n",
    "    var = np.array(t).var(axis=1).mean(axis=1)                        #(3.47)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.ylim(0, (bias2+var).max()+.01)\n",
    "    plt.plot(alpha_range, bias2, label=r\"bias$^2$\")\n",
    "    plt.plot(alpha_range, var, label=\"var\")\n",
    "    plt.plot(alpha_range, bias2+var, label=r\"bias$2$+var\")\n",
    "    plt.xlabel('$\\ln \\lambda$')\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.legend()\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "toggle()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,

   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Principle Component Regression\n",
    "\n",
    "PCR forms the derived input columns (principle components) and then regresses $y$ on a subset of those components. \n",
    "\n",
    "The main purposes of a principal component analysis are the analysis of data to identify patterns and finding patterns to reduce the dimensions of the dataset with minimal loss of information.\n",
    "\n",
    "We start with a 3-dimensional dataset that we reduce to an 2-dimensional dataset by dropping 1 dimension.\n",
    "\n",
    "We generate 40 3-dimensional samples randomly drawn from a multivariate Gaussian distribution. Assume that the samples stem from two different classes, where one half (i.e., 20) samples of our data set are labeled $\\mathcal{C}_1$ (class 1) and the other half $\\mathcal{C}_2$ (class 2), and mean vectors\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "\\mu_1 = \\mu_2 = \\begin{bmatrix}0\\\\0\\\\0\\end{bmatrix}\n",
    "\\end{align*}\n",
    "\n",
    "and covariance matrices\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "\\Sigma_1 = \\Sigma_2 = \\begin{bmatrix}1\\quad 0\\quad 0\\\\0\\quad 1\\quad0\\\\0\\quad0\\quad1\\end{bmatrix}\n",
    "\\end{align*}\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x576 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "np.random.seed(234)\n",
    "\n",
    "mu_vec1 = np.array([0,0,0])\n",
    "cov_mat1 = np.array([[1,0,0],[0,1,0],[0,0,1]])\n",
    "class1_sample = np.random.multivariate_normal(mu_vec1, cov_mat1, 20).T\n",
    "assert class1_sample.shape == (3,20), \"The matrix has not the dimensions 3x20\"\n",
    "\n",
    "mu_vec2 = np.array([1,1,1])\n",
    "cov_mat2 = np.array([[1,0,0],[0,1,0],[0,0,1]])\n",
    "class2_sample = np.random.multivariate_normal(mu_vec2, cov_mat2, 20).T\n",
    "assert class2_sample.shape == (3,20), \"The matrix has not the dimensions 3x20\"\n",
    "\n",
    "from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D\n",
    "from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import proj3d\n",
    "\n",
    "fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))\n",
    "ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')\n",
    "plt.rcParams['legend.fontsize'] = 10   \n",
    "ax.plot(class1_sample[0,:], class1_sample[1,:], class1_sample[2,:], 'o', \n",
    "        markersize=8, color='blue', alpha=0.5, label='class1')\n",
    "ax.plot(class2_sample[0,:], class2_sample[1,:], class2_sample[2,:], '^', \n",
    "        markersize=8, alpha=0.5, color='red', label='class2')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.title('Samples for class 1 and class 2')\n",
    "ax.legend(loc='upper right')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "we created two $3 \\times 20$ datasets - one dataset for each class - where each column can be pictured as a 3-dimensional vector\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "\\pmb x = \\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\\\ x_2 \\\\ x_3 \\end{pmatrix}\n",
    "\\end{align*}\n",
    "\n",
    "so that our dataset will have the form\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "\\pmb X = \\begin{pmatrix} x_{1_1}\\; x_{1_2} \\; ... \\; x_{1_{20}}\\\\ x_{2_1} \\; x_{2_2} \\; ... \\; x_{2_{20}}\\\\ x_{3_1} \\; x_{3_2} \\; ... \\; x_{3_{20}}\\end{pmatrix}\n",
    "\\end{align*}\n",
    "\n",
    "Because we don't need class labels for the PCA, let us merge the samples for our 2 classes into one $3 \\times 40$-dimensional array."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "all_samples = np.concatenate((class1_sample, class2_sample), axis=1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Computing the $p$-dimensional mean vector "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Mean Vector:\n",
      " [[0.77257186]\n",
      " [0.68324797]\n",
      " [0.43460518]]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "mean_x = np.mean(all_samples[0,:])\n",
    "mean_y = np.mean(all_samples[1,:])\n",
    "mean_z = np.mean(all_samples[2,:])\n",
    "mean_vector = np.array([[mean_x],[mean_y],[mean_z]])\n",
    "print('Mean Vector:\\n', mean_vector)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "###  Computing the Scatter Matrix\n",
    "\n",
    "The scatter matrix is computed by the following equation\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "S = \\sum\\limits_{k=1}^n (\\pmb x_k - \\pmb m)\\;(\\pmb x_k - \\pmb m)^\\intercal\n",
    "\\end{align*}\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\pmb m$ is the mean vector\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "\\pmb m = \\frac{1}{n} \\sum\\limits_{k=1}^n \\; \\pmb x_k\n",
    "\\end{align*}\n",
    "\n",
    "or alternatively `scatter_matrix = np.cov(all_samples) * (40 - 1)` the covariance matrix $\\times$ $(n-1)$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Scatter Matrix:\n",
      " [[39.35126181  4.22467775 12.74899364]\n",
      " [ 4.22467775 50.9168567  10.18400644]\n",
      " [12.74899364 10.18400644 66.86899978]]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "scatter_matrix = np.zeros((3,3))\n",
    "for i in range(all_samples.shape[1]):\n",
    "    scatter_matrix += (all_samples[:,i].reshape(3,1) - mean_vector).dot((all_samples[:,i].reshape(3,1) - mean_vector).T)\n",
    "print('Scatter Matrix:\\n', scatter_matrix)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Computing Eigenpairs"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Eigenvector 1: \n",
      "[[0.33730459]\n",
      " [0.39443594]\n",
      " [0.85477828]]\n",
      "Eigenvalue 1 from scatter matrix: 76.59928002932904\n",
      "----------------------------------------\n",
      "Eigenvector 2: \n",
      "[[ 0.93260098]\n",
      " [-0.01618419]\n",
      " [-0.36054609]]\n",
      "Eigenvalue 2 from scatter matrix: 34.349151694294285\n",
      "----------------------------------------\n",
      "Eigenvector 3: \n",
      "[[ 0.12837844]\n",
      " [-0.91878091]\n",
      " [ 0.37331034]]\n",
      "Eigenvalue 3 from scatter matrix: 46.188686560075034\n",
      "----------------------------------------\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "eig_val_sc, eig_vec_sc = np.linalg.eig(scatter_matrix)\n",
    "for i in range(len(eig_val_sc)):\n",
    "    eigvec_sc = eig_vec_sc[:,i].reshape(1,3).T\n",
    "\n",
    "    print('Eigenvector {}: \\n{}'.format(i+1, eigvec_sc))\n",
    "    print('Eigenvalue {} from scatter matrix: {}'.format(i+1, eig_val_sc[i]))\n",
    "    print(40 * '-')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Visualizing the eigenvectors**\n",
    "\n",
    "We plot the eigenvectors centered at the sample mean."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 504x504 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from matplotlib.patches import FancyArrowPatch\n",
    "\n",
    "class Arrow3D(FancyArrowPatch):\n",
    "    def __init__(self, xs, ys, zs, *args, **kwargs):\n",
    "        FancyArrowPatch.__init__(self, (0,0), (0,0), *args, **kwargs)\n",
    "        self._verts3d = xs, ys, zs\n",
    "\n",
    "    def draw(self, renderer):\n",
    "        xs3d, ys3d, zs3d = self._verts3d\n",
    "        xs, ys, zs = proj3d.proj_transform(xs3d, ys3d, zs3d, renderer.M)\n",
    "        self.set_positions((xs[0],ys[0]),(xs[1],ys[1]))\n",
    "        FancyArrowPatch.draw(self, renderer)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig = plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))\n",
    "ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')\n",
    "\n",
    "ax.plot(all_samples[0,:], all_samples[1,:], all_samples[2,:], 'o', markersize=8, color='green', alpha=0.2)\n",
    "ax.plot([mean_x], [mean_y], [mean_z], 'o', markersize=10, color='red', alpha=0.5)\n",
    "for v in eig_vec_sc.T:\n",
    "    a = Arrow3D([mean_x, v[0]], [mean_y, v[1]], [mean_z, v[2]], mutation_scale=20, lw=3, arrowstyle=\"-|>\", color=\"r\")\n",
    "    ax.add_artist(a)\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('x_values')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('y_values')\n",
    "ax.set_zlabel('z_values')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.title('Eigenvectors')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Choosing $k$ Largest Eigenvalues\n",
    "\n",
    "we are reducing a 3-dimensional feature space to a 2-dimensional feature subspace, we are combining the two eigenvectors with the highest eigenvalues to construct our $p \\times k$-dimensional eigenvector matrix $\\mathbf{W}$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "[(76.59928002932904, array([0.33730459, 0.39443594, 0.85477828])),\n",
       " (46.188686560075034, array([ 0.12837844, -0.91878091,  0.37331034])),\n",
       " (34.349151694294285, array([ 0.93260098, -0.01618419, -0.36054609]))]"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 13,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "eig_pairs = [(np.abs(eig_val_sc[i]), eig_vec_sc[:,i]) for i in range(len(eig_val_sc))]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Sort the (eigenvalue, eigenvector) tuples from high to low\n",
    "eig_pairs.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)\n",
    "eig_pairs"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": true
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Matrix W:\n",
      " [[ 0.33730459  0.12837844]\n",
      " [ 0.39443594 -0.91878091]\n",
      " [ 0.85477828  0.37331034]]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "matrix_w = np.hstack((eig_pairs[0][1].reshape(3,1), eig_pairs[1][1].reshape(3,1)))\n",
    "print('Matrix W:\\n', matrix_w)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Transforming the Samples\n",
    "\n",
    "In the last step, we use the $2 \\times 3$-dimensional matrix $\\mathbf{W}$ that we just computed to transform our samples onto the new subspace via the equation\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "y = \\mathbf{W}^\\intercal \\mathbf{x}\n",
    "\\end{align*}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

     "data": {

     "metadata": {

     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "transformed = matrix_w.T.dot(all_samples)\n",
    "plt.plot(transformed[0,0:20], transformed[1,0:20], 'o', markersize=7, color='blue', alpha=0.5, label='class1')\n",
    "plt.plot(transformed[0,20:40], transformed[1,20:40], '^', markersize=7, color='red', alpha=0.5, label='class2')\n",
    "plt.xlim([-4,4])\n",
    "plt.ylim([-4,4])\n",
    "plt.xlabel('x_values')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('y_values')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.title('Transformed samples with class labels')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### PCA Packages\n",
    "\n",
    "Now, that we have seen how a principal component analysis works, we can use the in-built `PCA()` class from the `matplotlib` library for our convenience in future applications. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",

    "from matplotlib.mlab import PCA as mlabPCA \n",
    "\n",
    "mlab_pca = mlabPCA(all_samples.T)\n",
    "\n",
    "print('PC axes in terms of the measurement axes scaled by the standard deviations:\\n', mlab_pca.Wt)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.plot(mlab_pca.Y[0:20,0],mlab_pca.Y[0:20,1], 'o', markersize=7, color='blue', alpha=0.5, label='class1')\n",
    "plt.plot(mlab_pca.Y[20:40,0], mlab_pca.Y[20:40,1], '^', markersize=7, color='red', alpha=0.5, label='class2')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.xlabel('x_values')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('y_values')\n",
    "plt.xlim([-4,4])\n",
    "plt.ylim([-4,4])\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.title('Transformed samples with class labels from matplotlib.mlab.PCA()')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "When we plot the transformed dataset onto the new 2-dimensional subspace, we observe that the scatter plots from our step by step approach and the `matplotlib.mlab.PCA()` class do not look identical. This is due to the fact that `matplotlib.mlab.PCA()` class scales the variables to unit variance prior to calculating the covariance matrices. This will eventually lead to different variances along the axes and affect the contribution of the variable to principal components.\n",
    "\n",
    "We can also use the `PCA` class from the `scikit-learn` machine-learning library. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.decomposition import PCA as sklearnPCA\n",
    "\n",
    "sklearn_pca = sklearnPCA(n_components=2)\n",
    "sklearn_transf = sklearn_pca.fit_transform(all_samples.T)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.plot(sklearn_transf[0:20,0],sklearn_transf[0:20,1], 'o', markersize=7, color='blue', alpha=0.5, label='class1')\n",
    "plt.plot(sklearn_transf[20:40,0], sklearn_transf[20:40,1], '^', markersize=7, color='red', alpha=0.5, label='class2')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.xlabel('x_values')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('y_values')\n",
    "plt.xlim([-4,4])\n",
    "plt.ylim([-4,4])\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.title('Transformed samples with class labels from matplotlib.mlab.PCA()')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "If we want to mimic the results produced by `scikit-learn`, we need change the signs of the eigenvectors produced by `scikit-learn`\n",
    "\n",
    "`sklearn_transf = sklearn_transf * (-1)`\n",
    "\n",
    "and subtract the mean vectors from the samples $\\mathbf{X}$ to center the data at the coordinate system's origin \n",
    "\n",
    "`transformed = matrix_w.T.dot(all_samples - mean_vector)`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x360 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "sklearn_transf = sklearn_transf * (-1)\n",
    "# sklearn.decomposition.PCA\n",
    "plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15,5))\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)\n",
    "plt.plot(sklearn_transf[0:20,0],sklearn_transf[0:20,1], 'o', markersize=7, color='blue', alpha=0.5, label='class1')\n",
    "plt.plot(sklearn_transf[20:40,0], sklearn_transf[20:40,1], '^', markersize=7, color='red', alpha=0.5, label='class2')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('x_values')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('y_values')\n",
    "plt.xlim([-4,4])\n",
    "plt.ylim([-4,4])\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.title('Transformed samples via sklearn.decomposition.PCA')\n",
    "\n",
    "# user-definied PCA\n",
    "plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)\n",
    "transformed = matrix_w.T.dot(all_samples - mean_vector)\n",
    "plt.plot(transformed[0,0:20], transformed[1,0:20], 'o', markersize=7, color='blue', alpha=0.5, label='class1')\n",
    "plt.plot(transformed[0,20:40], transformed[1,20:40], '^', markersize=7, color='red', alpha=0.5, label='class2')\n",
    "plt.xlim([-4,4])\n",
    "plt.ylim([-4,4])\n",
    "plt.xlabel('x_values')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('y_values')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.title('Transformed samples step by step approach')\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "In PCA, we are interested to find the directions (components) that maximize the variance in our dataset. The implicit assumption is that the response will tend to vary most in the directions of high variance of the inputs. Therefore, we project the entire set of data (without class labels) onto a different subspace via PCA and identify some important predictors."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Bayesian Regression\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider a simple linear model of the form $y(x, \\mathbf{w}) = -0.3 + 0.5 x$. We demonstrate how $p(\\mathbf{w} | \\mathbf{y}, \\mathbf{X})$ changes through learning\n",
    "\n",
    "- Figure \"prior/posterior\" shows the initial belief of $\\mathbf{w}$ and how it involves after knowing more data points. Based on Bayesian model, prior/posterior distribution is a normal distribution \n",
    "    \n",
    "    `multivariate_normal.pdf(w, mean=model.w_mean, cov=model.w_cov)` \n",
    "    \n",
    "    and the mean is approaching to the true value $(-.3, .5)$ from $(0,0)$.\n",
    "\n",
    "- The likelihood function provides a soft constraint that the line must pass close to the data point, where close is determined by the noise precision $\\beta$. We demonstrate $p(y_0|x_0, \\mathbf{w})$ for one point (at `end` position). Standardized pdf\n",
    "\n",
    "    `contour(w0, w1, multivariate_normal.pdf((-t_train[end-1: end] + w @ phi_train[end-1: end].T)*model.beta))`\n",
    "\n",
    "    enumerates all the values of $\\mathbf{w}$ and shows the probability that the response $y_0$ occurs. The graph always highlights a straight stripe near the true value $(-.3, .5)$ because any $\\mathbf{w}$ on the line $y_0 = w_0 + w_1 x_0$ has large likelihood function value.\n",
    "\n",
    "- The lines in Figure \"data space\" are based on randomly generated $\\mathbf{w}$ following current belief."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

     "data": {

    "def linear(x):\n",
    "    return -0.3 + 0.5 * x\n",
    "\n",
    "w0, w1 = np.meshgrid(\n",
    "    np.linspace(-1, 1, 100),\n",
    "    np.linspace(-1, 1, 100))\n",
    "w = np.array([w0, w1]).transpose(1, 2, 0)\n",
    "\n",
    "x_train, t_train = create_data(linear, 20, 0.1, [-1, 1])\n",
    "x_test = np.linspace(-1, 1, 100)\n",
    "\n",
    "phi_train = Polynomial(1).dm(x_train)\n",
    "phi_test  = Polynomial(1).dm(x_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "model = Bayesian(alpha=2., beta=25.)\n",
    "\n",
    "for beg, end in [[0, 0], [0, 1], [1, 2], [2, 3], [3, 20]]:\n",
    "    model.fit(phi_train[beg: end], t_train[beg: end])\n",
    "    \n",
    "    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1,3,figsize=(16, 4))\n",
    "    if end > 0:\n",
    "        axes[0].scatter(-0.3, 0.5, s=200, marker=\"x\")\n",
    "        # Use standardization.\n",
    "        axes[0].contour(w0, w1, multivariate_normal.pdf((-t_train[end-1: end] + w @ phi_train[end-1: end].T)*model.beta))\n",
    "    axes[0].set_xlabel(\"$w_0$\")\n",
    "    axes[0].set_ylabel(\"$w_1$\")\n",
    "    axes[0].set_title(\"likelihood\")    \n",
    "    \n",
    "    axes[1].scatter(-0.3, 0.5, s=200, marker=\"x\")\n",
    "    axes[1].contour(w0, w1, multivariate_normal.pdf(w, mean=model.w_mean, cov=model.w_cov))\n",
    "    axes[1].set_xlabel(\"$w_0$\")\n",
    "    axes[1].set_ylabel(\"$w_1$\")\n",
    "    axes[1].yaxis.set_label_coords(-.12,.5)\n",
    "    axes[1].set_title(\"prior/posterior\")\n",
    "    \n",
    "    axes[2].scatter(x_train[:end], t_train[:end], s=20, facecolor=\"none\", edgecolor=\"steelblue\", lw=1)\n",
    "    # use posterior dist to generate w, and then w is used for prediction\n",
    "    axes[2].plot(x_test, phi_test @ np.random.multivariate_normal(model.w_mean, model.w_cov, size=6).T, c=\"orange\")\n",
    "    axes[2].set_xlim(-1, 1)\n",
    "    axes[2].set_ylim(-1, 1)\n",
    "    axes[2].set_xlabel(\"$x$\")\n",
    "    axes[2].set_ylabel(\"$y$\") \n",
    "    axes[2].yaxis.set_label_coords(-.12,.5)\n",
    "    axes[2].set_title(r\"data space $n={}$\".format(end))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.show()"
   ]

    "## Bayesian Prediction\n",
    "\n",
    "We use polynomial curve fitting as an illustration of the predictive distribution for Bayesian linear regression models. It provides a confidence region on predictions"
   ]

    "x_train, t_train = create_data(sinusoidal, 10, 0.25)\n",

    "x_train, t_train = create_data(sinusoidal, 25, 0.25)\n",
    "x_test = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)\n",
    "t_test = sinusoidal(x_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "phi_train = Gaussian(np.linspace(0, 1, 9), 0.1).dm(x_train)\n",
    "phi_test  = Gaussian(np.linspace(0, 1, 9), 0.1).dm(x_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "model = Bayesian(alpha=2e-3, beta=2)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(18, 8))\n",
    "for i, [beg, end] in enumerate([[0, 1], [1, 2], [2, 4], [4, 8], [8, 25]]):\n",
    "    t, t_std = model.fit(phi_train[beg: end], t_train[beg: end]).predict_dist(phi_test)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.subplot(2,3,i+1)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.scatter(x_train[:end], t_train[:end], s=100, facecolor=\"none\", edgecolor=\"steelblue\", lw=2)\n",
    "    plt.plot(x_test, t_test, label=\"$\\sin(2\\pi x)$\")\n",
    "    plt.plot(x_test, t, label=\"fitting\")\n",
    "    plt.fill_between(x_test, t - t_std, t + t_std, color=\"orange\", alpha=0.5)\n",
    "    plt.xlim(-0.02, 1)\n",
    "    plt.ylim(-2, 2)\n",
    "    plt.title(r\"data size $n={}$\".format(end))\n",
    "    plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Evidence Approximation\n",
    "\n",
    "The predictive distribution is\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "p(t|\\mathbf{y}, \\alpha, \\beta) = \\mathcal{N} \\left( t | \\mathbf{m}^\\intercal_{n} \\phi(\\mathbf{x}), \\sigma^2_n(\\mathbf{x}) \\right) \\nonumber\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "The key is to obtain hyperparameters $\\alpha, \\beta$ as well as $\\mathbf{m}_n$.\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Initialization: $k = 0$, $\\alpha^0 = \\alpha_0$ and $\\beta^0 = \\beta_0$\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Find eigenvalues $\\lambda_i$, $i=0, \\ldots, M-1$ such that \n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\\left(\\beta \\Phi^\\intercal \\Phi \\right) \\mathbf{u}_i = \\lambda_i \\mathbf{u}_i \\nonumber\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Let\t\t\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\\gamma^k = \\sum_{i=0}^{M-1} \\frac{\\lambda_i}{\\alpha^k+\\lambda_i},~ \\alpha^{k+1} = \\frac{\\gamma^k}{\\mathbf{w}^\\intercal_{mean} \\mathbf{w}_{mean}} \\text{ and } \\frac{1}{\\beta^{k+1}} = \\frac{1}{N - \\gamma} \\sum_{i=1}^{N} \\left( y_i - \\mathbf{w}^\\intercal_{mean} \\phi(x_i) \\right)^2 \\nonumber\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "    where $\\mathbf{w}_{mean} = \\mathbf{m}_n = \\beta \\mathbf{S}_n\\mathbf{\\Phi}^\\intercal \\mathbf{y}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. If $|\\alpha^{k+1} - \\alpha^{k}| + |\\beta^{k+1} - \\beta^{k}| <$ threshold, then return $\\alpha, \\beta$, else $k = k+1$ and go to step 2.\n",
    "\n",
    "For the polynomial regression model with degree from 0 to 8, we find the optimal value of the evidence function. The empirical bayes approach is applied and the evidence favours the model with degree $= 3$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "def cubic(x):\n",
    "    return x * (x - 5) * (x + 5)\n",
    "\n",
    "x_train, t_train = create_data(cubic, 30, 10, [-5, 5])\n",
    "x_test = np.linspace(-5, 5, 100)\n",
    "t_test = cubic(x_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "phi_train = [Polynomial(i).dm(x_train) for i in range(8)]\n",
    "\n",
    "models = [Empirical(alpha=100., beta=100.).fit(phi, t_train, max_iter=100) for phi in phi_train]\n",
    "evidences = [model.log_evidence(phi, t_train) for model, phi in zip(models, phi_train)]\n",
    "\n",
    "opt_degree = int(np.nanargmax(evidences))\n",
    "\n",
    "phi_test = Polynomial(opt_degree).dm(x_test)\n",
    "t, t_std = models[opt_degree].predict_dist(phi_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.scatter(x_train, t_train, s=50, facecolor=\"none\", edgecolor=\"steelblue\", label=\"observation\")\n",
    "plt.plot(x_test, t_test, label=\"x(x-5)(x+5)\")\n",
    "plt.plot(x_test, t, label=\"prediction\")\n",
    "plt.fill_between(x_test, t - t_std, t + t_std, alpha=0.5, label=\"std\", color=\"orange\")\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.plot(evidences)\n",
    "plt.title(\"Model evidence\")\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"degree\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"log evidence\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  }
